<font color="#FF0000">WASHING MACHINES AND SNAKES</font><br>
<tt>Sat Aug  9 20:09:44 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I have a washing machine that has cycles. I put in dirty clothes and detergent, and out come clean clothes. That is a simple productive event. I can even choose what cycle I want. Long, short, heavy duty, etc. I can predict every time that clean clothes will come out. <br><br>
Human cycles are a little different. Sometimes it takes successive iterations, many iterations, in fact, to achieve an objective. It is always two steps forward and one step back. However, when one does the same thing over and over and expects different results each time, and one does not get different results, it is called insanity.<br><br>
There comes a time when excuses, glib talk, dismissal of the facts, and psychological mirrors finally fail, and someone does remember the repetitious inappropriate behavior and its effects. We are all eventually called upon to face the music of our transgressions. Repetitious failure to do so is called incredulity, or, more simply put, a lack of credibility.<br><br>
The absence of credibility leads to a loss of honor, and a situation that has no redeeming virtue or lasting constructive effect upon the state of affairs. It is nothing more than a proof of the theory of chaos.<br><br>
Stories of serpents are ancient but very appropriate metaphors for the darker side of human behavior. Not only do they escape transformation when they shed their skin, but they all have forked tounges. Something in the DNA, I am told. Poor snakes! They always seem to be eating their tails, too!  
